# <project-name>

## Overview

`<project-name>` is an AI-native RAG application scaffolded with the Forge
framework's `ai-native-rag` archetype. It pairs a Rust backend (RAG pipeline +
in-repo LLM gateway proxy + MCP servers) with a Qwik streaming web surface,
backed by Postgres/pgvector (HNSW), Temporal, Zitadel (OIDC), and the
SigNoz/OBI/Coroot observability trio. Protobuf definitions in `shared/protos/`
are the single source of truth for all cross-layer contracts.

> **Status**: this archetype is a `candidate` (`scaffoldable: false`). The
> backbone (templates + scaffolder body + verify-then-pin) lands in B.7.2;
> promotion to `stable` / `scaffoldable: true` is gated on a green B.7.6 harness
> (`ADR-B7-2-001`). Until then `forge init --archetype ai-native-rag` refuses
> cleanly (exit 3).

## Architecture

```text
<project-name>/
├── backend/             # Rust — Cargo workspace (RAG pipeline + LLM gateway + MCP)
│   ├── llm_gateway/     # thin axum proxy, OpenAI-compatible, tier-aware hooks
│   ├── mcp/             # rmcp MCP servers (stdio + streamable-HTTP)
│   └── rag/             # chunking · embeddings · hybrid retrieval · re-ranking
├── frontend/web-public/ # Qwik streaming UI (Connect-ES v2)
├── infra/               # pgvector HNSW + Temporal + Zitadel + observability
├── shared/protos/       # Protobuf contracts (source of truth)
├── .forge/              # Forge framework assets
├── .claude/             # Claude Code agents, commands, skills
├── Taskfile.yml         # task dev/test/lint/proto/release
└── docker-compose.dev.yml
```

- `backend/` — Rust Cargo workspace. Beyond the shared substrate (Connect
  transport, Temporal workers, Zitadel/OTel), it ships three net-new layers:
  - **`llm_gateway/`** — a thin axum proxy (decision A) exposing an
    OpenAI-compatible API to the frontend and forwarding to Mistral-EU / vLLM.
    Tier-aware refusal hooks, prompt-audit span (Article IX.6), token budget +
    kill switch (Article XI.5), PII guard (Article XI.6), and a mandatory
    non-AI fallback path. See `.forge/standards/global/llm-gateway.md`.
  - **`mcp/`** — Model Context Protocol servers built on `rmcp`, exposing tools
    over both stdio (local dev) and streamable-HTTP (prod, OAuth 2.1 →
    Zitadel/Envoy-OIDC). See `.forge/standards/global/mcp-servers.md`.
  - **`rag/`** — the retrieval pipeline: chunking + embeddings, hybrid
    retrieval (vector + BM25 + RRF), coarse→exact re-ranking, pgvector HNSW
    (`vector_cosine_ops`). Heavy work runs as Temporal activity-only workers.
    See `.forge/standards/global/rag-patterns.md`.
- `frontend/web-public/` — Qwik streaming UI. The streaming transport detail
  (SSE / WebTransport) ships in a later brick (B.7.10); the baseline here is a
  non-streaming request/response surface over Connect-ES v2. No Flutter mobile
  surface ships in this archetype (web-public only).
- `infra/` — reuses the B.8 substrate by reference; the RAG-specific additions
  are the pgvector HNSW index definitions and the `llm-gateway` service wiring.
- `shared/protos/` — Buf-managed `.proto` files; never duplicated in layer code.

## Prerequisites

Install the following tools before running anything locally:

- **Rust ≥ 1.80** — <https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install> (`cargo --version`)
- **Buf ≥ 1.30** — <https://buf.build/docs/installation> (`buf --version`)
- **Node.js 24** — for the Qwik web-public surface (`node --version`)
- **Docker + Docker Compose** — <https://docs.docker.com/get-docker/> (`docker compose version`)
- **Task (go-task)** — <https://taskfile.dev/installation/> (`task --version`)

## Quickstart

1. Copy the environment file and fill in local values:

   ```bash
   cp .env.example .env
   # edit .env — DB password, ports, LLM gateway upstream + API key, tier
   ```

2. Start the compose stack (Postgres/pgvector + backend + observability):

   ```bash
   task dev:up
   ```

3. Regenerate Protobuf stubs after any `.proto` change:

   ```bash
   task proto
   ```

4. Run all layer tests:

   ```bash
   task test
   ```

## AI-First non-negotiables

This archetype enforces the Constitution's AI-First articles in the scaffolded
code:

- **Mandatory fallback (XI.5)** — every AI feature has a non-AI fallback. The
  LLM gateway degrades (cached / refusal) when the upstream is down or a token
  budget is exceeded; embeddings fall back to the in-process `LocalEmbedder`.
- **PII explicit consent (XI.6)** — the gateway carries a PII guard; the local
  embedding path keeps text in-process (zero egress) for sovereign tiers.
- **Prompt audit + token budget (IX.6)** — every prompt is traced with an audit
  span and a token-budget check before the upstream call.
- **Tier awareness** — selection of cloud vs local providers is driven by
  `FORGE_EU_TIER`; T3 forces zero-egress local paths. The runtime refusal rules
  themselves are enforced by a later brick (Janus AI, B.7.9); this scaffold
  ships the tier-aware *hooks*.

## Development workflow

- All code changes go through the Forge pipeline:
  `/forge:new` → specify → design → plan → implement → review → archive.
  Read `.forge/constitution.md` for the non-negotiable rules.
- Commit messages **must** use scoped Conventional Commits. Allowed scopes:
  `backend`, `frontend`, `infra`, `protos`, `forge`, `docs`, `ci`.
- Cross-layer changes (touching ≥ 2 layers simultaneously) are routed through
  **Janus** — see root `CLAUDE.md` for the routing policy.

